Been coming for years and with the recent revamp it is one of the only (if not THE only) places in Harlem that you can feel equally at home in the morning having a cup of coffee and taking a meeting as a cafe which then transforms into the perfectly relaxing environment to have an amazing dinner in the evening.  Kudos to the team, I’m almost afraid to leave this review for the fear of the secret getting out. Anyway enjoy.  ;-)

Consistently inconsistent. I live across the road from this establishment and have for a couple of years, my wife insisted we go when we first moved in, and we went and my pasta was glued together. We went back once more and the experience was bad again - I vowed that I wouldn't go back. Settepani recently had a facelift and the new al fresco style is quite refreshing and a wonderful addition to the block- the pastries and gelato at the counter have added a new grab-and-go element to the restaurant and we've quite enjoyed getting quick bites to eat. Enticed by Instagram diners at brunch I was convinced to once again give the dining experience a go. Our coffee was prompt and service friendly but our meals took an incredibly long time to arrive, tables all around us were receiving their meals late,  many ostensibly incorrect or poorly cooked - when ours finally arrived, the main features were delicious but our side potatoes were rock solid lumps. The server didn't offer replacement potatoes, only a side salad as an alternative as it was apparent that the potatoes wouldn't come any time soon. Once again I won't be returning for a dine-in experience as all 3 visits I've made involving meal prepared in the kitchen have been severely disappointing. I want to like this place on all fronts, but it's clear that Settepani can't find cooks to save itself.

After " escaping " NYC for a few days " in the countryside " of NYState, I returned tired after a longish Greyhound ride back into the City that never sleeps.....I had booked the "Soulfood" B&B on 120th..and passed this local on the corner - checked it out quickly, checked into the B&B  and returned to this place on the corner...it was late...9pm.  A lady at the bar ( customer ) assured me that all was good here, a Diner enjoying his meal at the bar confirmed same...so , grabbed a table "vite fais"...( quickly ) !! - and ordered some Chard and a Pasta dish....the lamb looked good, but passed this time ( the lady next table said it was great !)  My food arrived quickly, wine, bread and olive oil too...atmosphere was super, curiously, many spoke french - in an Italian styled local...??!! What goes ? Dunno, but the food, atmosphere and friendliness of all ( guests as well as "personal" excellent....and I speak from very many years of experience, in many restaurants spread all around the world. Here was someplace ' special'..., I followed it up with a cocktail at the bar...- and enjoyed the closing hours... Return ? A definite yes; although I live thousands of miles away in Paris, I would love this place to be my "local" .....and will happily return next year, after apparent remodelling...super local, very friendly and warm atmosphere - seldom !!!

This is a nice location in a lovely part of Harlem. Every time I see it I dream of how a could transform this restaurant into a really popular destination, because right now it does not live up to its price or location. Both the quality of food and service are below par for a medium priced Italian restaurant. The food is well presented but can be bland. The service is too much before you order then non-existent afterwards. I can't believe how poorly this place is run and how much it could improve with new management
I love this place. The food is amazing and services was excellent. This is my new spot! Love Love this place'
Nice restaurant, great for a group and just a couple to find a relax spot where to enjoy some home made omelets and tasty potatoes, the coffee is good and the service is fast and friendly

The food is excellent. The drinks are excellent. The entertainment they provide every Thursday and Sunday is excellent. One of their workers Lynell is so adorable wish all the workers had his fun easygoing spirit. Im usually their for brunch in the A.M on the weekends I love this place.

Settepani is the perfect place to have a quiet breakfast/brunch on a weekend morning in Harlem. The bread is fresh and delicious, so I always order French toast or toast on the side with eggs and bacon. The brunch cocktails (mimosa and strawberry bellini) are also very good.
The service is the worst in Harlem.  I will never visit this space ever again.

my wife and i went to settepani for the first time a few nights ago. we had a very enjoyable evening. the place is nicely designed with good lighting, has a relaxed atmosphere, nice crowd, charming service and good food (i ordered orange/red beet salad, dark bean soup and trout - i was totally satisfied), the wine (french chardonnay) was very good, the espresso was superb (just needs that lemon peel twist on the side) and the sambuca was served generously. we enjoyed the evening tremendously. part of the great evening was the fabulous annette st. john singing jazzy songs backed by her great trio. overall the prices were fair, but the appetizers are a little pricey and could/should cost about 25% less ...
(Translated by Google) I have been there with my love bread and fantastic breakfasts  (Original) Ci sono stato col mio amore pane e colazioni fantastiche
Fine italian dining, very nice inside, was a little pricy, if your not into seafood, you don't have a lot of options

This spot is okay, but still a welome addition to the Harlem community which could use more cafes. If you want coffee it will do, sometimes the desserts are good. The service could be better. Long story short, go here if you do not want to expect much.
